VALUES
(40, 24, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'the days of Noe', 7, 22, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Noe''', 'Νῶε (Noe, G3575) - Noah, a significant figure representing faithfulness amidst judgment. This reference implies a contrast between Noah''s righteousness and the surrounding wickedness, highlighting the call for believers to embody faith in a corrupt world.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3575", "description": "Strong''s number for Noah."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'so shall also the coming', 29, 53, 'question', 'Reflection on Readiness', 'What does it mean to be ready for the coming of the Son of Man in your life today? Considering the complacency of those in Noah''s time, how can you actively prepare your heart and mind for Christ''s return?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'eating and drinking', 56, 75, 'connection', 'Pre-Flood Lifestyle', 'This phrase echoes Genesis 6:11-13, where the earth was filled with violence and corruption just before the flood. The mundane activities of ''eating and drinking'' highlight the complacency and moral disregard of society at that time. This connection emphasizes the contrast between ordinary life and impending divine judgment. Just as in Noah''s day, many may be engrossed in daily routines while ignoring spiritual truths.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:11", "description": "Describes the moral state of humanity before the flood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'until the day that Noe entered into the ark', 110, 153, 'theology', 'Impending Judgment', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of God''s patience and the suddenness of His judgment. Many scholars believe that just as Noah was a herald of impending disaster, Christians are called to be watchful and prepared for Christ''s return. The entrance into the ark symbolizes safety and obedience amidst judgment, reflecting the broader theme of salvation through faith.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'marrying and giving in marriage', 77, 108, 'greek', 'Cultural Norms', 'γάμος (gamos, G1062) - marriage, wedding. This Greek term represents the cultural practices of establishing familial bonds and societal structures. The mention of ''marrying'' reflects the normalcy of life that can distract from spiritual readiness. Understanding the term helps underline the idea that even good and normal activities can lead to spiritual apathy if they overshadow the urgency of one''s relationship with God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1062", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for marriage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'as in the days that were before the flood', 4, 45, 'question', 'Reflection on Readiness', 'What parallels can we draw between our current societal behaviors and those of the pre-flood world? In what ways might we be similarly unprepared for Christ''s return, engrossed in daily life? This verse invites us to examine our priorities and readiness for divine intervention.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'knew not until the flood came', 4, 33, 'connection', 'Link to Genesis Account', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 7:22, which states that all in whose nostrils was the breath of life died in the flood. The parallel emphasizes the suddenness of judgment, as those in Noah''s time were unaware of the impending disaster until it was too late. This connection serves as a warning about spiritual preparedness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 7:22", "description": "This verse highlights the unexpected nature of the flood judgment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'took them all away', 39, 57, 'theology', 'Nature of Divine Judgment', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of divine judgment as both comprehensive and sudden. Many scholars believe that it illustrates the finality of God''s judgment, where separation occurs between those who are prepared and those who are not, echoing the theme of accountability in Christian teaching.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'so shall also the coming of the Son of man be.', 59, 105, 'question', 'Reflection on Preparedness', 'In what ways does the unexpected nature of the flood challenge your understanding of Christ''s return? How does this urgency to be spiritually awake influence your daily decisions and relationships?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'knew not until the flood came', 4, 33, 'greek', 'Greek Insight on ''knew''', 'γινώσκω (ginōskō, G1097) - to know, to perceive, to understand. This term emphasizes a lack of awareness or spiritual insight among the people during Noah''s time, highlighting the need for vigilance and understanding in our faith journey.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1097", "description": "This Strong''s number corresponds to the Greek term for knowledge and perception."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 40, 40, 'kjv', 'Then shall two be in the field;', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Reference to Noah''s Days', 'This phrase resonates with the context of judgment seen in Genesis 6:5-7, where the wickedness of humanity leads to the flood. Just as Noah''s time was marked by everyday activities amid imminent judgment, this verse illustrates how life continues normally before Christ''s return. It serves as a reminder to remain vigilant.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:5", "description": "Describes the state of humanity before the flood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 40, 40, 'kjv', 'the one shall be taken, and the other left.', 32, 75, 'theology', 'Separation in Judgment', 'This passage suggests a separation that reflects the broader theological theme of judgment and salvation. Many scholars believe it points to the final judgment, where individuals are distinguished based on their faith in Christ. This dichotomy highlights the urgency of personal faith and readiness for Christ''s return.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 40, 40, 'kjv', 'Then shall two be in the field;', 0, 31, 'greek', 'Field in Greek', 'ἀγρός (agros, G68) - field, land, or cultivated area. This term signifies not just physical labor but also the everyday life and responsibilities of people. It emphasizes that the return of Christ will interrupt even the most mundane activities.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G68", "description": "Indicates the Greek term for field."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 41, 41, 'kjv', 'Two women shall be grinding at the mill;', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Labor and Readiness', 'This imagery of women grinding at the mill is reminiscent of Ruth 2:2, where Ruth gleaned in the fields. Both scenarios highlight ordinary daily activities, reinforcing the theme of being vigilant and prepared in everyday life. The contrast of one being taken and the other left serves as a poignant reminder of the unexpected nature of the Lord''s coming.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ruth 2:2", "description": "Ruth''s daily labor parallels the ordinary setting of vigilance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 41, 41, 'kjv', 'the one shall be taken, and the other left.', 41, 84, 'theology', 'Divine Judgment', 'This passage illustrates the concept of divine selection and judgment, where not all are taken into eternal life. Many scholars believe this aligns with the broader biblical theme of separation between the righteous and the unrighteous, indicating that readiness for Christ''s return is crucial.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of being taken or left."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 41, 41, 'kjv', 'Two women shall be grinding at the mill;', 0, 40, 'question', 'Vigilance in Daily Life', 'How does this mundane activity of grinding at the mill reflect the importance of being spiritually alert in our daily routines? In what ways can we incorporate readiness for the Lord''s return into our everyday tasks?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 41, 41, 'kjv', 'the one shall be taken, and the other left.', 41, 84, 'greek', 'Greek Terms in Focus', 'ἀφεθῇ (aphethe, G863) - to be taken away, released, or forgiven. This term suggests a decisive action, emphasizing the suddenness of the event where one is taken and the other is left, highlighting the gravity of being prepared.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G863", "description": "Indicates the nature of the taking away."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 42, 42, 'kjv', 'Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come.', 0, 63, 'connection', 'Preparedness in Scripture', 'This call to ''watch'' resonates with 1 Thessalonians 5:2-6, where Paul admonishes believers to be alert and sober, emphasizing the unexpected return of the Lord. The connection underscores the theme of vigilance in the Christian life, reinforcing that believers are called to live in a state of readiness, aware that Christ''s return could occur at any moment.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:2-6", "description": "Paul''s exhortation to be vigilant and prepared for the Lord''s return."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 42, 42, 'kjv', 'Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come.', 0, 63, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Watch''', 'γρηγορέω (grēgoreō, G1127) - to be awake, to be watchful. This term emphasizes the active state of alertness expected of believers. It implies not just passive waiting, but an engaged readiness that involves spiritual vigilance and moral diligence in the face of uncertainty regarding the timing of Christ''s return.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1127", "description": "Strong''s number for ''watch'' in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 42, 42, 'kjv', 'Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come.', 0, 63, 'theology', 'Doctrine of Christ''s Return', 'This verse reflects the widely-accepted Christian doctrine of the imminent return of Christ, a theme prevalent in the New Testament. Many scholars believe that the uncertainty of the timing serves as a motivation for believers to live faithfully and responsibly, fostering a readiness that permeates all aspects of life. This doctrine reinforces the belief in accountability before God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight into the implications of Christ''s return for daily living."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 42, 42, 'kjv', 'Watch therefore: for ye know not what hour your Lord doth come.', 0, 63, 'question', 'Personal Readiness', 'In light of this exhortation to ''watch,'' what practical steps can you take to ensure you are spiritually prepared for the Lord''s return? Consider how you can cultivate a lifestyle that reflects vigilance and readiness in your daily actions and decisions.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 43, 43, 'kjv', 'if the goodman of the house had known', 20, 57, 'connection', 'Awareness of the Unexpected', 'This phrase echoes 1 Thessalonians 5:2, which states, ''For yourselves know perfectly that the day of the Lord so cometh as a thief in the night.'' Both passages emphasize the necessity of vigilance and preparedness for the unexpected return of the Lord. The connection highlights the spiritual call to be alert and ready, as the timing of divine events is often unknown to us.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:2", "description": "The day of the Lord as a thief in the night"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 43, 43, 'kjv', 'the goodman of the house', 23, 47, 'greek', 'Greek Term Insight', 'οἰκοδεσπότης (oikodespotēs, G3617) - householder, master of the house. This term reflects the responsibility and authority of the householder. In biblical times, the goodman was tasked with the welfare of the household, which underscores the importance of being vigilant and prepared for any intrusions, particularly in a spiritual sense.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3617", "description": "Strong''s number for \u03bf\u1f30\u03ba\u03bf\u03b4\u03b5\u03c3\u03c0\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 43, 43, 'kjv', 'he would have watched', 94, 115, 'theology', 'The Call to Vigilance', 'This passage suggests that vigilance is a key aspect of Christian life. Many scholars believe that being spiritually alert is essential for believers, as it prepares them for Christ''s return. This is in line with the parable of the ten virgins (Matthew 25:1-13), where preparedness directly correlates with one''s fate at the return of the bridegroom.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 25:1-13", "description": "Parable of the ten virgins emphasizing preparedness"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 43, 43, 'kjv', 'would not have suffered his house to be broken up', 121, 170, 'question', 'Reflecting on Spiritual Security', 'What does it mean for us today to ensure that our ''house''—our spiritual lives—are secure from being ''broken up''? How can we actively guard against spiritual complacency, knowing that Christ''s return is unknown? This reflection can guide us in assessing our own vigilance and readiness in faith.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 44, 44, 'kjv', 'Therefore be ye also ready', 0, 26, 'theology', 'Readiness and Vigilance', 'This passage emphasizes the necessity of spiritual preparedness. Many scholars believe that this call to be ''ready'' relates to the broader Christian doctrine of vigilance in faith, as echoed in 1 Thessalonians 5:2-6, where believers are encouraged to remain alert and sober, anticipating the coming of the Lord. This readiness is not merely passive waiting but an active engagement in living out one''s faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:2-6", "description": "Encourages vigilance and readiness for the Lord''s return."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 44, 44, 'kjv', 'for in such an hour as ye think not', 28, 63, 'connection', 'Unexpected Timing', 'The theme of unexpected timing is prevalent throughout Scripture. A notable connection is found in Luke 12:40, which states, ''Be ye therefore ready also: for the Son of man cometh at an hour when ye think not.'' This consistent message underscores the importance of living in a state of readiness, as the return of Christ can occur at any moment, challenging believers to maintain a faithful lifestyle.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 12:40", "description": "Reiterates the call to readiness for Christ''s return."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 44, 44, 'kjv', 'the Son of man cometh', 64, 85, 'greek', 'Son of Man in Greek', 'υἱὸς τοῦ ἀνθρώπου (huios tou anthrōpou, G5207) - Son of Man; a title used by Jesus that emphasizes His identification with humanity and His role as the eschatological judge. This term is significant as it encapsulates both His divinity and humanity, highlighting the dual nature of Christ and His authority in the final judgment.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5207", "description": "Strong''s number for ''Son of Man.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 44, 44, 'kjv', 'be ye also ready', 10, 26, 'question', 'Personal Readiness', 'What does it mean for you personally to ''be ye also ready''? In what areas of your life do you feel a need to prepare for the return of Christ? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper spiritual growth and a more intentional approach to faith.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 45, 45, 'kjv', 'Who then is a faithful and wise servant', 0, 39, 'theology', 'Faithful Servant Concept', 'This passage introduces the concept of stewardship in the Kingdom of God. Many scholars believe that being a ''faithful and wise servant'' implies a responsibility to manage not only one''s own life but also the lives of others entrusted to one''s care. This reflects the broader biblical theme of accountability, as seen in parables like the Talents (Matthew 25:14-30), where servants are rewarded or punished based on their faithfulness in stewardship.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 45, 45, 'kjv', 'whom his lord hath made ruler over his household', 41, 89, 'connection', 'Leadership and Responsibility', 'This phrase connects to Luke 12:42, which also discusses the role of a ''faithful and wise steward.'' The emphasis on being appointed by the master highlights the divine authority in leadership roles. Understanding this connection underscores the importance of being accountable to God in our leadership, whether in the church, family, or community.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 12:42", "description": "Similar teaching on stewardship and accountability."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 45, 45, 'kjv', 'to give them meat in due season?', 91, 123, 'greek', 'Significance of ''meat''', 'ἔθνος (ethnos, G1484) - nation, people, or group. While ''meat'' in this context typically refers to sustenance, it can also symbolize spiritual nourishment. The call to provide ''meat in due season'' suggests that leaders should offer timely and relevant guidance, echoing themes found in John 21:15-17 about feeding the sheep. This connection deepens our understanding of spiritual leadership.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1484", "description": "Strong''s number for ''ethnos'', indicating broader implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 45, 45, 'kjv', 'Who then is a faithful and wise servant', 0, 39, 'question', 'Personal Stewardship Reflection', 'In what ways can you embody the qualities of a ''faithful and wise servant'' in your daily responsibilities? Reflecting on how you manage your time, resources, and relationships can lead to deeper spiritual growth and a better understanding of your role in God''s household.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'Blessed is that servant,', 0, 24, 'theology', 'Understanding ''Blessed''', 'The term ''blessed'' signifies a state of divine favor and happiness, often linked to obedience and faithfulness in Scripture. Many scholars believe that this blessing is not only a future reward but also an indication of present joy in living according to God''s will. This reflects the broader biblical theme that true fulfillment comes from serving faithfully in God''s kingdom.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'whom his lord when he cometh', 25, 53, 'connection', 'Parable of the Talents', 'This phrase connects with the Parable of the Talents in Matthew 25:19-21, where faithful servants are rewarded for their diligence. Both passages emphasize the importance of being actively engaged in service while awaiting the master''s return. This connection highlights the expectation of accountability in stewardship of what God has entrusted to us.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 25:21", "description": "This verse reinforces the theme of stewardship and faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'shall find so doing.', 54, 74, 'greek', 'Key Greek Term', 'ποιῶν (poiōn, G4160) - doing, making, performing. This term emphasizes active participation in service. It suggests that the servant''s continual actions are critical, highlighting that faith is not merely a belief but is manifested through actions. This underscores the call to live out one''s faith through diligent service.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4160", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'Blessed is that servant,', 0, 24, 'question', 'Reflecting on Faithfulness', 'What does it mean for you to be found ''so doing'' when Christ returns? In what areas of your life is God calling you to be a faithful servant? Reflecting on this can guide your actions today in light of eternal implications.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'Verily I say unto you, That he shall make him ruler over all his goods.', 0, 71, 'connection', 'Authority and Stewardship', 'This verse resonates with Luke 12:42-44, where Jesus discusses the faithful and wise steward. Both passages emphasize the reward for faithful service and the responsibilities that come with authority. The connection highlights the biblical principle that those who are faithful in little will be entrusted with much, reinforcing the idea of stewardship in God''s kingdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 12:42-44", "description": "Jesus speaks about stewardship and rewards for faithfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'ruler over all his goods', 46, 70, 'greek', 'Greek Understanding of ''Ruler''', 'ἐπίσκοπος (episkopos, G1985) - overseer, guardian, or supervisor. This term conveys a sense of responsibility and care for those under one''s authority. Understanding this word deepens the meaning of the ''ruler'' as not merely a position of power, but one of stewardship and accountability.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1985", "description": "Greek term indicating oversight and responsibility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'he shall make him ruler over all his goods.', 28, 71, 'theology', 'Divine Reward for Faithfulness', 'This passage suggests that God rewards faithfulness in stewardship. Many scholars believe it reflects the broader biblical theme of divine promotion based on character and diligence. It underscores the idea that earthly responsibilities can lead to greater heavenly rewards, illustrating God''s justice and generosity in the kingdom.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the rewards for faithful service."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'Verily I say unto you', 0, 21, 'question', 'Understanding Christ''s Authority', 'What does it mean for us to hear ''Verily I say unto you'' as a declaration of Christ''s authority? How does this shape our understanding of His promises regarding rewards and responsibilities as servants in His kingdom?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'that evil servant', 11, 28, 'theology', 'Nature of the Evil Servant', 'This passage highlights the moral responsibility of those entrusted with authority. The term ''evil servant'' suggests a deliberate choice to act against the will of the master, contrasting with the faithful servant who embodies diligence and loyalty. Many scholars believe this serves as a warning against complacency and moral decay among believers, urging vigilance in one''s duties.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'My lord delayeth his coming;', 53, 81, 'connection', 'Delay of the Master', 'This phrase reflects a theme found in 2 Peter 3:4, where scoffers question the promise of Christ''s return, claiming, ''Where is the promise of his coming?'' This connection emphasizes the danger of losing faith in the master''s return, which can lead to moral failures. Both passages serve as a reminder of the importance of steadfastness in faith during perceived delays.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "2 Peter 3:4", "description": "This verse illustrates the skepticism towards the promise of Christ''s return."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'if that evil servant shall say in his heart,', 8, 52, 'greek', 'Heart''s Intentions', 'καρδία (kardia, G2588) - heart, mind, character. This term signifies not only the emotional center but also the will and intellect of a person. The use of ''heart'' here indicates that the servant''s thoughts and intentions are critical, suggesting that one''s inner dialogue can lead to actions that defy their responsibilities.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2588", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word meaning ''heart''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'delayeth his coming;', 61, 81, 'question', 'Reflection on Delay', 'What implications does the phrase ''delayeth his coming'' have for my daily life and spiritual readiness? How can I remain faithful and diligent in service, despite the apparent delay of Christ''s return?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'his fellowservants', 25, 43, 'connection', 'Servant Relationships', 'This phrase connects to James 4:11, which warns against speaking evil of one another. The act of smiting fellowservants serves as a stark reminder of the importance of treating others with respect and kindness, reflecting the heart of Christ''s teachings about community and love.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:11", "description": "Highlights the importance of mutual respect among believers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'to eat and drink with the drunken', 49, 82, 'theology', 'Moral Compromise', 'This passage suggests a moral decline where the servant indulges in excess and association with those lacking self-control. Many scholars believe this reflects a broader theological theme of vigilance and moral integrity, warning against complacency and the dangers of worldly influences.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'to eat and drink with the drunken', 49, 82, 'greek', 'Drunkenness in Context', 'μεθύσκω (methusko, G3184) - to be drunk or intoxicated. This term highlights the seriousness of moral decay and indulgence, emphasizing the spiritual dangers that arise when one chooses to associate with those who are careless in their behavior.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3184", "description": "Indicates the term used for drunkenness in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'his fellowservants', 25, 43, 'question', 'Reflection on Actions', 'What might lead a servant to turn against fellowservants, and how can we guard against similar attitudes in our relationships today? How does this passage challenge you to reflect on your own interactions with others in your community?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 24, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'The lord of that servant shall come in a day when he looketh not for him, and in an hour that he is not aware of,', 0, 113, 'connection', 'Unexpected Timing of Christ''s Return', 'This verse echoes the teaching found in 1 Thessalonians 5:2-3, which states that the day of the Lord will come like a thief in the night. Both passages emphasize that the return of Christ will happen unexpectedly, urging believers to remain vigilant and prepared. This connection is crucial as it reinforces the idea that complacency can lead to dire consequences.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Thessalonians 5:2-3", "description": "Emphasizes the unexpected nature of Christ''s return."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');